<table width="90%" border="0" bordercolor="Red" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
	<tr>
		<td class="black12">August 28th, 2002</td>
		<td align="right" class="black12">Contact: Sunmoon   </td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td align="center" class="black12" colspan="2">
		<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bordercolor="333300">
			<tr>
				<td bgcolor="666633" align="center" class="white14"><b>Warder's Protection follow-up</b></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td bgcolor="e2e6d3" class="black12" colspan="2" align="left">
				Until today, the system wouldn't allow us to make spells that mutually bounced off of each other without a significant chunk of fairly ugly coding. <br><br>The only thing we could do would be to make the spells overwrite the other way. <br><br>Unfortunately, since Warder's has a +HP component, "Make the spells overwrite the other way" isn't an acceptable answer. <br><br>A person with sufficiently low HP and Brell's could then be killed by a person casting Warder's on them, as it overwrote their added hit points. (As we all know, in Norrath, a distinct lack of hit points is the leading cause of death.) <br><br>We'd have essentially traded one problem (DS overwriting HP buff) for the identical one (Worse HP buff overwriting a better HP buff.) <br><br>We don't like to intentionally make a spells with fewer HP overwrite spells with greater HP. No spell that has infinite potential for abuse can really be allowed, or it absolutely will be, as unfortunate as that is. It's rare, but it does happen. <br><br>The only alternative to that was a seven or eight way list of hardcoded spells, which isn't a valid answer, either. It just makes the stacking system even less maintainable. <br><br>That's why we waited until we could get a proper, flexible, cleaner system in place that we could use to solve this problem *and many others* all at the same time. <br><br>It's about fixing it the right way, once, as opposed to having this one get fixed with a hack, then the next one fixed with another hack, then the next.... and so on, where each progressive fix takes even longer as someone has to go through and figure out what all of the (growing) spaghetti means every time. <br><br>Hope that made sense at this hour. <br><br>Scott Hartsman<br>Technical Director, EverQuest
				</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td bgcolor="e2e6d3" class="black12" colspan="2" align="middle">
				
